{{Slovenes}}
The '''Slovene minority in Italy (1920–1947)''' was the indigenous [[Slovenes|Slovene]] population—approximately 327,000 out of a total population of 1.3<ref name="SacroEgoismo2012">Lipušček, U. (2012) ''Sacro egoismo: Slovenci v krempljih tajnega londonskega pakta 1915'', Cankarjeva založba, Ljubljana. {{ISBN|978-961-231-871-0}}</ref> million ethnic Slovenes at the time<ref name=Cresciani_ClashOfCivilisations>Cresciani, Gianfranco (2004) [https://docs.google.com/open?id=0B1aAzmXBjZO5eFQySUlrdTBYRkk Clash of civilisations], Italian Historical Society Journal, Vol.12, No.2, p.4</ref>—that was cut from the remaining three-quarters of the Slovene ethnic community after the [[First World War]]. According to the secret [[Treaty of London (1915)|Treaty of London]] and the [[Treaty of Rapallo (1920)|Treaty of Rapallo]] in 1920, the former [[Austrian Littoral]] and western part of the former [[Inner Carniola]] were annexed to the [[Kingdom of Italy (1861–1946)|Kingdom of Italy]]. Whereas only a few thousand Italians were left in the new South Slavic{{efn-lr|In the beginning called the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]], renamed Yugoslavia in 1929.''}} state, a population of half a million Slavs,<ref name="HehnP_Low_Dishonest_Decade">Hehn, Paul N. (2005) [https://books.google.com/books?id=nOALhEZkYDkC&pg=PA45&dq=%22the+treaty+left+half+a+million+Slavs+inside+Italy+while+only+a+few+hundred+Italians&lr=&sig=ACfU3U1d_etPPJL-3k8nsYws4mfuun44sQ A Low Dishonest Decade: Italy, the Powers and Eastern Europe, 1918-1939.], Chapter 2, ''Mussolini, Prisoner of the Mediterranean''</ref> both Slovenes and Croats, was subjected to forced [[Italianization]] until the [[fall of Fascism]] in Italy.

==Italianization==
At the end of the 19th century, [[Trieste]] was the largest Slovene city, with more [[Slovenes|Slovene]] inhabitants than even [[Ljubljana]].<ref>Plut-Pregelj, Leopoldina, & Carole Rogel. 2007. ''The A to Z of Slovenia.'' Lanham, MD: Scarecrow Press, p. 467.</ref> After being ceded from multiethnic Austria, the Italian nationalist milieus sought to make Trieste a ''città italianissima'', committing a series of attacks led by [[Black Shirts]] against Slovene shops, libraries, lawyers' offices, and the central place of the rival community in the [[Trieste National Hall]].<ref>Morton, Graeme; R. J. Morris; B. M. A. de Vries (2006).[https://books.google.si/books?id=8vEQg87bUJ0C&pg=PA89&dq=89&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EEQwUtulGcPfswbR1ICwBw&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=89&f=false Civil Society, Associations, and Urban Places: Class, Nation, and Culture in Nineteenth-century Europe], [[Ashgate Publishing]], UK</ref> Forced [[Italianization]] followed, and by the mid-1930s several thousand Slovenes, especially intellectuals from the Trieste region, emigrated to the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]] and to [[South America]].

Notable Slovenes affected by Italianization included the poet [[Srečko Kosovel]] and the writer [[Boris Pahor]]. Slovenes that emigrated included the writers [[Vladimir Bartol]] and [[Josip Ribičič]], the legal theorist [[Boris Furlan]], and the architect [[Viktor Sulčič]]. In order to fight the Fascist repression, the [[militant anti-fascist]] organization [[TIGR]] was formed in 1927.

==Today==
{{main|Slovene minority in Italy}}
The estimated number of today's Slovene minority in Italy is 83,000 to 100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minorityrights.org/1616/italy/slovenes.html |title=The world directory of minorities and indigenous peoples |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904060246/http://www.minorityrights.org/1616/italy/slovenes.html |archivedate=2015-09-04 |df= }}</ref>

==Notable members of the Slovene minority in Italy (1920–1947)==
* [[Boris Pahor]] (born 1913)
* [[Vladimir Bartol]] (1903–1967)
* [[Milko Bambič]] (1905–1991)

